{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17493073","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17493073"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T06:55:11+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T06:55:11+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1215"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1215","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1215"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.06,0.04,0.24,0.03,0.63]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1215"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"101442"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1215","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1215"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1215"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"83881"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"14"},{"type":"tags","id":"22"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"37"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"589"},{"type":"tags","id":"1240"},{"type":"tags","id":"4812"},{"type":"tags","id":"4818"},{"type":"tags","id":"4935"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"12801"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"9083"},{"type":"contributions","id":"39794"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"101442","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/101442"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 25-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with a three-day history of foul-smelling vaginal discharge. She has no other symptoms. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications except for the combined oral contraceptive pill.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. Speculum examination reveals a homogeneous creamy-grey discharge. The vaginal pH is 5.0. Microscopy of a vaginal swab shows clue cells. Addition of 10% potassium hydroxide to the vaginal fluid produces a fishy odour.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following organisms is most likely to be responsible for these findings?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Candida albicans","Chlamydia trachomatis","Trichomonas vaginalis","Neisseria gonorrhoeae","Gardnerella vaginalis"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with all four Amsel criteria for bacterial vaginosis: elevated vaginal pH \u0026gt;4.5, clue cells on microscopy, homogeneous discharge, and a positive whiff test (fishy odour with potassium hydroxide). \u003Cstrong\u003E\u003Cem\u003EGardnerella vaginalis\u003C/em\u003E\u003C/strong\u003E is the predominant organism in bacterial vaginosis, which occurs when there is an overgrowth of anaerobic bacteria with concurrent reduction in protective lactobacilli.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E\u003Cem\u003ECandida albicans\u003C/em\u003E\u003C/strong\u003E typically causes a thick, white, \u0027cottage cheese\u0027 discharge with vulval itching and normal vaginal pH. Microscopy would show pseudohyphae rather than clue cells.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E\u003Cem\u003EChlamydia trachomatis\u003C/em\u003E\u003C/strong\u003E infection is often asymptomatic but may cause cervicitis with mucopurulent discharge. It would not cause clue cells or a positive whiff test.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E\u003Cem\u003ETrichomonas vaginalis\u003C/em\u003E\u003C/strong\u003E infection typically presents with a frothy yellow-green discharge and a \u0027strawberry\u0027 cervix on examination. Microscopy would show motile trichomonads rather than clue cells.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E\u003Cem\u003ENeisseria gonorrhoeae\u003C/em\u003E\u003C/strong\u003E typically causes cervicitis with purulent discharge, dysuria, and post-coital bleeding. Gram stain would show intracellular gram-negative diplococci rather than clue cells.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ETreatment of bacterial vaginosis involves oral or intravaginal metronidazole or clindamycin. While bacterial vaginosis is not strictly a sexually transmitted infection, it is associated with sexual activity and new sexual partners. Currently treatment for a partner with a penis is not recommended though trials are showing promising results of reduced recurrence.  If the partner has a vagina then it would be recommended to screen for bacterial vaginosis and treat simultaneously.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Bacterial vaginosis is diagnosed using the Amsel criteria: elevated vaginal pH \u003E4.5, clue cells, homogeneous discharge, and positive whiff test.","Gardnerella vaginalis overgrowth in bacterial vaginosis occurs due to disruption of normal vaginal flora with reduction in protective lactobacilli.","The presence of clue cells on microscopy is pathognomonic for bacterial vaginosis."],"references":["Reiter S, Spadt SK.  Bacterial vaginosis: a primer for clinicians. Postgrad Med 2019; 131:8-18. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/30424704/","Bacterial Vaginosis. In: Australian STI management guidelines for use in Primary Care [online]. 2022 [cited 2023 April 1]. Available from: https://sti.guidelines.org.au/sexually-transmissible-infections/bacterial-vaginosis/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"83881"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1215"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"83881","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/83881"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-05-01T22:53:15+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-06-26T09:15:03+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1215"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"101442"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"14","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/14"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udda0","name":"Infectious Diseases","synonyms":["ID"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2021-05-21T07:51:58+09:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"22","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/22"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf53","name":"Gynaecology","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"3"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"37","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/37"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf46","name":"Sexual Health","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","